					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div role=3D"note" c=
lass=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about the binary=
 operation <i>mod(<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>a,n</span>)</i>. For the <i>(mod <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">n</span>)</i> notation, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">Modular arithme=
tic</a>. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modul=
o_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Modulo (disambiguation)"=
>Modulo (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=
=3D"display:none">Computational operation</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computing" title=3D"Computin=
g">computing</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" =
title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a>, the <b>modulo operation</b> returns =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remainder" title=3D"Remainder"=
>remainder</a> or signed remainder of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a>=
, after one number is divided by another, the latter being called the <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular=
 arithmetic">modulus</a></i> of the operation.
</p><p>Given two positive numbers <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> a=
nd <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i=
></span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> (often abbreviated =
as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> mod <i>n</i></span>) is the remainder o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D=
"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a=
</i></span> by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>, where <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">dividend</a> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Divisor" title=3D"Divisor">divisor</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulo#cite_n=
ote-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For example, the expression "5 mod 2" evaluates to 1, because 5 divi=
ded by 2 has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotient" title=3D"=
Quotient">quotient</a> of 2 and a remainder of 1, while "9 mod 3" would eva=
luate to 0, because 9 divided by 3 has a quotient of 3 and a remainder of 0=
.
</p><p>Although typically performed with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></=
span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> both being <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a>, many co=
mputing systems now allow other types of numeric operands. The range of val=
ues for an integer modulo operation of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></sp=
an> is 0 to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1</span>. <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> mod 1 is always 0.
</p><p>When exactly one of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> or <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> is negative, the basic definition breaks=
 down, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_languages" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Programming languages">programming languages=
</a> differ in how these values are defined.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Variants_of_the_definition"=
>Variants of the definition</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DModulo&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Variants of the definition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the result of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modulo</a> operati=
on is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_class" title=
=3D"Equivalence class">equivalence class</a>, and any member of the class m=
ay be chosen as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representative_(ma=
thematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Representative (mathematics)">re=
presentative</a>; however, the usual representative is the <b>least positiv=
e residue</b>, the smallest non-negative integer that belongs to that class=
 (i.e., the remainder of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
dean_division" title=3D"Euclidean division">Euclidean division</a>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Modulo#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, other conventions are possible. C=
omputers and calculators have various ways of storing and representing numb=
ers; thus their definition of the modulo operation depends on the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" title=3D"Programmin=
g language">programming language</a> or the underlying <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_hardware" title=3D"Computer hardware">hardwar=
e</a>.
</p><p>In nearly all computing systems, the quotient <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>q</i></span> and the remainder <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i></span>=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> divided by <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle n\neq 0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A0<!-- =E2=89=A0 --></mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n\neq 0}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5920e98ff3dd1cb41e01f76243300450c958d5e5" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:5.656ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n\n=
eq 0}"></span> satisfy the following conditions:
</p>
<table role=3D"presentation" class=3D"numblk" style=3D"margin-left: 3.2em;"=
><tbody><tr><td class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-e=
lement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" =
style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"=
 alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}&amp;q\in \mathbb {Z} \\&amp;a=
