begin{aligned}&amp;q\in \mathbb {Z} \\&amp;a=3Dnq+r\quad (n\neq 0)\\&amp;|r=
|&lt;|n|\end{aligned}}}"></span></td> <td></td> <td class=3D"nowrap"><span =
id=3D"math_1" class=3D"reference nourlexpansion" style=3D"font-weight:bold;=
">1</span></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>This still leaves a sign ambiguity if the remainder is non-zero: two pos=
sible choices for the remainder occur, one negative and the other positive;=
 that choice determines which of the two consecutive quotients must be used=
 to satisfy equation (1). In number theory, the positive remainder is alway=
s chosen, but in computing, programming languages choose depending on the l=
anguage and the signs of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> or <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulo#cite_note-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(programming_langu=
age)" title=3D"Pascal (programming language)">Pascal</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL_68" title=3D"ALGOL 68">ALGOL 68</a>, for e=
xample, give a positive remainder (or 0) even for negative divisors, and so=
me programming languages, such as C90, leave it to the implementation when =
either of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> or <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>a</i></span> is negative (see the table under <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Modulo#In_programming_languages">=C2=A7&nbsp;In programmin=
g languages</a> for details). Some systems leave <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>a</i></span> modulo 0 undefined, though others define it as <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>.
</p>
<div><ul><li><figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Divmod_truncated.svg" class=3D"m=
